<BLOCK2><TI>CLAIM</TI>
<P><P1>1. THE PLAINTIFF CLAIMS AGAINST THE DEFENDANTS LEGEND 3D CANADA INC. and LEGEND 3D INC., JOINTLY AND SEVERALLY:
<P2>(a) a declaration that he was wrongfully dismissed from his employment with them;</P2>
<P2>(b) damages in the amount of $236,715.50, subject to all statutory withholdings and deductions and less amounts the Plaintiff has already received, on account of 21 months' pay in lieu of notice of the Defendants' termination of a fixed-term employment agreement;</P2>
<P2>(c) in the alternative to the damages sought in paragraph 1(b), damages in the amount of $67,500, subject to all statutory withholdings and deductions and less amounts that the Plaintiff has already received, on account of salary in lieu of six months' reasonable notice of termination at common law;</P2>
<P2>(d) damages for the Plaintiff's loss of his entire benefit package for the 21 month period described in paragraph 1(a), above; or, alternatively, damages for such loss for the six month period of notice of termination described in paragraph 1(c);</P2>
<P2>(e) damages in the amount of $169,082.50 for breach of contract, or on the alternative bases of restitution or <EM>quantum meruit</EM>; and</P2>
<P2>(f) damages in the amount of $25,000 on the basis of a negligent misrepresentation made to him.</P2></P1>
<P1>2. THE PLAINTIFF CLAIMS AGAINST THE DEFENDANTS JOSEPH CASHION AND SARITA MANDANNA, JOINTLY AND SEVERALLY
<P2>(a) pursuant to the section 130 of the Ontario <EM>Business Corporations Act</EM>, R.S.O. 1990, c. B.16 (the &ldquo;OBCA&rdquo;) and section 81 of the Ontario <EM>Employment Standards Act, 2000</EM>, S.O. 2000, c. 41 (the &ldquo;ESA&rdquo;) damages for unpaid debts not exceeding six months' wages that became payable while they were directors of the Defendant Legend 3D Canada Inc. for services performed by the Plaintiff to Legend 3D Canada Inc., and in particular, on account of the amounts specified in paragraphs 1(e), above, subject to the aforementioned limitations of the OBCA and ESA;</P2></P1>
<P1>3. THE PLAINTIFF CLAIMS AGAINST ALL DEFENDANTS, JOINTLY AND SEVERALLY:
<P2>(a) the costs of this action on a substantial indemnity basis plus all taxes thereon;</P2>
<P2>(b) pre-judgment and post-judgment interest pursuant to the rates prescribed in the <EM>Courts of Justice Act</EM> R.S.O. 1990, c.C.43; and</P2>
<P2>(c) such further and other relief as this Honourable Court deems just.</P2></P1></P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI>The Parties</TI>
<P><P1>4. The Plaintiff, Andrew Rhinehart (&ldquo;Rhinehart&rdquo;), is an individual residing in West Palm Beach, Florida, USA. At all material times, he was an employee of the Defendants.</P1>
<P1>5. The Defendant, Legend 3D Canada Inc. (&ldquo;Legend 3D Canada&rdquo;), is a business incorporated pursuant to the laws of Ontario. Its head office is located in Toronto, Ontario. Legend 3D Inc. (&ldquo;Legend 3D&rdquo;) is a business incorporated pursuant to the laws of the United States. Both Defendants <UNDER>(the &ldquo;Corporate Defendants&rdquo;)</UNDER> are related entities that operate under common control in the digital media industry. At all material times, they were joint employers of Rhinehart.</P1>
<P1>6. The Defendant, Joseph Cashion (&ldquo;Cashion&rdquo;), is an individual residing in Toronto, Ontario. At all material times, he was a director of the Defendant, Legend 3D Canada.</P1>
<P1>7. The Defendant, Sarita Mandanna (&ldquo;Mandanna&rdquo;), is an individual residing in Toronto, Ontario. At all material times, she was a director of the Defendant, Legend 3D Canada.</P1></P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI>History of Employment and Dismissal</TI>
<P><P1>8. Rhinehart commenced employment with Legend 3D in September 2012 as a Compositor. In the years that followed, he worked in San Diego and then in Los Angeles in various capacities. While in Los Angeles, in the summer of 2016, Jeff Brownlee, Legend 3D's Vice President, Human Resources, contacted him to tell him that a Compositing Supervisor position had opened up at Legend 3D Canada in Toronto and that Legend 3D wanted him to fill the role.</P1>
<P1>9. Rhinehart, who had only lived in the United States, was intrigued by the offer but was concerned about moving to another country. He was enjoying his work with Legend 3D in the United States; and while living in the United States he was surrounded by friends, a girlfriend, and family. He needed to be confident that if he was to go through the inconvenience of moving to Toronto, it would be on the basis that Legend 3D's offer was a serious one and the job relatively secure.</P1>
<P1>10. In subsequent discussions with Brownlee, Brownlee informed Rhinehart that Legend 3D would want him to commit to working in Toronto for at least one year. Brownlee further assured Rhinehart that the job would be available to him for up to three years if Rhinehart wanted it. Rhinehart was also told that if he accepted the role, he would receive a substantial salary increase (from approximately $101,000 CDN to $135,000 CDN).</P1>
<P1>11. In convincing him to take the position, company representatives also spoke positively about the Canadian health care system and suggested that Rhinehart would be required to work, on average, only 40 hours per week.</P1>
<P1>12. Based on the foregoing representations, Rhinehart accepted the position in Toronto. He then received a letter from Brownlee for presentation to the Canadian government to obtain a work permit. The letter confirmed the above-noted terms of his employment.</P1>
<P1>13. In the months leading up to his move to Toronto in December 2016, Rhinehart rearranged his life. He gave up his apartment, sold his car, put his belongings in storage and moved to Canada with as little as possible. He bought a new wardrobe of winter clothes. Rhinehart also made arrangements to fly his 14 year old daughter across the Canadian-American border during holidays and breaks from school. None of this was an easy task.</P1>
<P1>14. Rhinehart landed in Toronto on December 31, 2016 and started working for Legend 3D Canada as Compositing Supervisor on January 2, 2017. In that role, he supervised between 120 and 150 visual effects artists at any given time, working on feature films. He was involved in hiring and training, and worked with the company's production department to meet critical deadlines.</P1></P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI>Misrepresentations and Breach of Contract</TI>
<P><P1>15. Soon after Rhinehart commenced employment for Legend 3D Canada, he quickly realized that he had been misled about his hours of work. Despite the fact that he was told that his average working hours would be limited to about 40 per week, he was required to work between 10 and 14 hours a day or 70 to 90 hours a week, with little (if ever any) time off in between. There were many months in which Rhinehart worked consecutive days without a day off. He complained about his hours of work repeatedly to his senior producer Chris McClintock, and his production department managers Neha Pasricha and Ashley Merla, to no avail.</P1>
<P1>16. Legend 3D Canada advised Rhinehart of his dismissal on February 6, 2018. The dismissal took effect on March 30, 2018.</P1>
<P1>17. At the time of his dismissal, Rhinehart was earning $135,266 CDN per annum and participated in an employer-sponsored group benefits insurance program. He was 33 years old.</P1></P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI>Damages</TI>
<P><P1>18. In light of the foregoing, Rhinehart states that he was employed by the <UNDER>Corporate</UNDER> Defendants in Canada under a three-year fixed-term employment agreement. It was an express or implied term of this agreement that the <UNDER>Corporate</UNDER> Defendants could not terminate his employment without providing him with advanced notice of termination or pay in lieu of such notice representing the difference between three years and the amount of time he actually worked for the <UNDER>Corporate Defendants</UNDER> in Toronto.</P1>
<P1>19. As of March 30, 2018, Rhinehart worked for the Defendants in Toronto for 15 months. He is therefore owed 21 months of pay for the balance of his contract, equal to $236,715.50, less statutory deductions and withholdings and amounts he received from the <UNDER>Corporate</UNDER> Defendants following his dismissal. Rhinehart is additionally entitled to damages <UNDER>from them</UNDER> for the loss of his benefits subsequent to March 30, 2018.</P1>
<P1>20. In the alternative, Rhinehart states that it was an implied term of his contract of employment with the <UNDER>Corporate</UNDER> Defendants that they could not terminate his employment in Toronto without providing him with reasonable advanced notice of termination or payment of damages in lieu of such notice at common law. In light of his 33 years of age, over five years of service to the Defendants, the character of his employment, and other factors, he is entitled to his total compensation prorated over six months (or damages for the loss thereof), less the value of payments made to him or benefits continued subsequent to his dismissal.</P1>
<P1>21. Rhinehart further states that he is entitled to a lump sum payment of $169,082.50 <UNDER>from the Corporate Defendants</UNDER>, being his salary prorated over 15 months of work up to March 31, 2018. He is entitled to such compensation on a contractual, restitutionary, or <EM>quantum meruit</EM> basis on account of the fact that he worked, on average, roughly twice as many hours as he was told that he would need to work. Rhinehart additionally states that such compensation unpaid constitutes a debt pursuant to s. 130 of the OBCA and s. 81 of the ESA for which Cashion and Mandanna are personally liable, jointly and severally, under such legislation, to a degree not exceeding six months of Rhinehart's wages.</P1>
<P1>22. Rhinehart states that the <UNDER>Corporate</UNDER> Defendants are liable to him in the amount of $25,000 on the basis of a negligent misrepresentation. The <UNDER>Corporate</UNDER> Defendants advised Rhinehart that he could work in Canada for three years; Rhinehart relied upon such representation in deciding to move to Toronto; and the <UNDER>Corporate</UNDER> Defendants breached such representation to his detriment shortly after he did so. The <STRIKE>Defendants</STRIKE> Plaintiff's losses include but are not limited to moving and travel expenses.</P1>
<P1>23. Rhinehart proposes that this action be tried in the City of Toronto.</P1></P>
