<BLOCK1><TI>STATEMENT OF DEFENCE</TI>
<P>1. The Defendants admit the allegations contained in paragraphs 4, 5 and 16 of the Statement of Claim.</P>
<P>2. The Defendants deny the allegations contained in paragraphs 1 through 3, 6 through 8, 10, 11, 12, 14, 15, and 17 through 22 of the Statement of Claim.</P>
<P>3. The Defendants have no knowledge in respect of the allegations contained in paragraphs 9 and 13 of the Statement of Claim.</P>
<BLOCK2><TI>THE PARTIES</TI>
<P>4. The Defendant, Legend 3D Inc., (&ldquo;Legend 3D&rdquo;) is a business incorporated pursuant to the laws of of the United States of America and is in the business of providing digital media services.</P>
<P>5. The Defendant, Legend 3D Canada Inc. (&ldquo;Legend 3D Canada&rdquo;), is a corporation duly incorporated pursuant to the laws of the Province of Ontario.</P>
<P>6. Joseph Cashion and Sarita Mandanna (collectively the &ldquo;Directors&rdquo;) are individuals residing in Toronto, Ontario and were the Directors of Legend 3D Canada.</P>
<P>7. Legend 3D Canada and Legend 3D (collectively referred to as the &ldquo;Corporate Defendants&rdquo;) state that the Plaintiff, Andrew Rhinehart, was employed in the position of Compositing Supervisor on an indefinite term employment contract at the time his employment was terminated without cause on February 6, 2018.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI>BACKGROUND</TI>
<P>8. On or about November 26, 2012, the Plaintiff was hired by the Corporate Defendants in the position of Junior Stereo Compositor to work out of its Los Angeles location with the employment to end on April 5, 2013.</P>
<P>9. The Plaintiff executed an offer of employment on November 26, 2012 (&ldquo;Offer of Employment No. 1&rdquo;). The Offer of Employment No. 1 specifically provides that all disputes shall be resolved through binding arbitration and states:
<QUOTE><P>All of us at Legend are very excited about you joining our team and look forward to a beneficial and fruitful relationship. <UNDER>However, should any dispute arise with respect to your employment or the termination of that employment, we both agree that such dispute shall be conclusively resolved by final binding and confidential arbitration</UNDER> in accordance with the Voluntary Labor Arbitration Rules of the American Arbitration Association (AAA) in San Diego, rather than by a jury court or administrative agency. The Company will bear those expenses unique to arbitration. [Emphasis Added]</P></QUOTE></P>
<P>10. The Plaintiff also executed an Arbitration Agreement on November 26, 2012, prior to the commencement of his employment (hereinafter &ldquo;Arbitration Agreement No. 1&rdquo;). Arbitration Agreement No. 1 states, <EM>inter alia</EM>, the following:
<QUOTE><P>Legend 3D Inc. (&ldquo;Legend&rdquo;) and <UNDER>I each agree to submit to final and binding arbitration any and all disputes that we could otherwise pursue in court that arise from or relate in any way to my recruitment, hiring, employment, or the termination of my employment, with Legend</UNDER>. This includes, without limitation, any claim against Legend or any of its employees or agents based on any state or federal statute (including claims for employment discrimination, retaliation or harassment, unpaid wages, or based on the California Labour Code), <UNDER>as well as any common law claim</UNDER> (including claims for breach of contract or breach of implied covenant of good faith and fair dealing, wrongful discharge, defamation, <UNDER>misrepresentation</UNDER>, fraud, and infliction of emotional distress), but excludes claims for workers' compensation benefits, state disability benefits, or state unemployment benefits. [Emphasis Added]</P></QUOTE></P>
<P>11. Arbitration Agreement No. 1 also contains various terms and conditions which include the following:
<P1>a) The arbitration shall be conducted by a single neutral arbitrator;</P1>
<P1>b) The arbitration shall proceed in accordance with the then-current rules of the American Arbitration Association for resolution of employment disputes;</P1>
<P1>c) The arbitration shall take place in the City of San Diego;</P1>
<P1>d) Legend 3D shall pay the arbitrator's fee and will bear all other administrative charges beyond those that the employee would have otherwise had to pay if he or she filed a lawsuit in Court;</P1>
<P1>e) The arbitrator shall have the power to award any type of relief that would be available in a Court of competent jurisdiction; and,</P1>
<P1>f) The arbitrator's award shall be final and binding upon the parties and may be entered as a judgment in any Court of competent jurisdiction.</P1></P>
<P>12. The Plaintiff's employment was extended due to additional projects and as such, the Plaintiff executed a second Offer of Employment on February 18, 2013 (Offer of Employment No. 2&rdquo;). The Offer of Employment No. 2 provides, <EM>inter alia</EM>, that the Plaintiff's employment would cease on June 21, 2013. Further, it includes an identical provision as Offer of Employment No. 1 requiring all disputes to be resolved via arbitration and as cited at paragraph 9 herein.</P>
<P>13. The Plaintiff's employment was terminated in or around June 2013 due to a shortage of work.</P>
<P>14. The Plaintiff was rehired in or around August 2013 in the position of Junior Stereo Compositor and executed a third Offer of Employment dated June 20, 2013 (&ldquo;Offer of Employment No. 3&rdquo;). The Offer of Employment No. 3 provides, <EM>inter alia</EM>, that the Plaintiff would commence employment on August 12, 2013 and includes an identical provision as Offer of Employment No. 1 requiring all disputes to be resolved via arbitration and as cited at paragraph 9 herein.</P>
<P>15. The Offer of Employment No. 3 also provides that the Plaintiff's employment would cease on February 28, 2014.</P>
<P>16. The Plaintiff also executed a second Arbitration Agreement on August 12, 2013 (&ldquo;Arbitration Agreement No. 2&rdquo;). Arbitration Agreement No. 2 is identical to Arbitration Agreement No. 1.</P>
<P>17. The Corporate Defendants extended the Plaintiff's employment for a fourth time and as such, the Plaintiff executed a further Offer of Employment on December 18, 2013 (&ldquo;Offer of Employment No. 4&rdquo;). The Offer of Employment No. 4 provides that the Plaintiff's employment shall end on June 2, 2014 and includes an identical provision as Offer of Employment No. 1 requiring all disputes to be resolved via arbitration and as cited at paragraph 9 herein.</P>
<P>18. The Plaintiff's employment was further extended in June 2014 on an indefinite term basis. In or around December 2014, the Plaintiff was promoted to the position of Lead Compositor.</P>
<P>19. In or around December 2016, the Corporate Defendants offered certain employees based in Los Angeles the opportunity to transfer to its office in the City of Toronto. The transfer was strictly optional. The Plaintiff accepted the offer to transfer to the City of Toronto.</P>
<P>20. The Plaintiff was required to apply for a temporary work permit from the Government of Canada to enable him to legally work in Ontario.</P>
<P>21. The Defendants state that a letter was provided to the Canada Border Services Agency of the Government of Canada in support of the Plaintiff's temporary work permit application to increase the likelihood the Plaintiff's request for a work permit would be approved. Similar letters were provided in support of all applications by employees of the Corporate Defendants who sought to transfer to Toronto.</P>
<P>22. The Plaintiff successfully received the work permit and commenced employment in Toronto on January 3, 2017 in the position of Compositing Supervisor.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI>THE DISPUTE IS SUBJECT TO BINDING ARBITRATION</TI>
<P>23. As pled in the Statement of Claim, this action is related to or arises out of the Plaintiff's recruitment, hiring, employment or the termination of his employment and as such, is subject to binding private arbitration pursuant to the terms and conditions of Arbitration Agreement No. 1, Arbitration Agreement No. 2 and the four Offers of Employment. Therefore, this action cannot be maintained.</P>
<P>24. The Defendants do not waive the provisions requiring private arbitration as specified in Arbitration Agreement No. 1, Arbitration Agreement No. 2 or the four Offers of Employment by issuance of this Statement of Defence.</P>
<P>25. The Defendants plead that pursuant to Arbitration Agreement No. 1, Arbitration Agreement No. 2 and the Offers of Employment, the Ontario courts do not have jurisdiction to adjudicate the dispute between the Plaintiff and the Defendants and that this proceeding ought therefore to be dismissed.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI>NO DAMAGES</TI>
<P>26. In the alternative, if the Plaintiff is capable of maintaining this action, which is not admitted but specifically denied, the Defendants specifically deny that the Plaintiff is entitled to the amounts sought and puts the Plaintiff to the strict proof thereof.</P>
<BLOCK3><N><EM>a</EM>.</N><TI><EM>There was no Fixed-Term Employment Agreement</EM></TI>
<P>27. The Defendants specifically deny that the Plaintiff was employed pursuant to a three year fixed-term employment agreement as alleged and puts the Plaintiff to the strict proof thereof.</P>
<P>28. The Defendants state that the Plaintiff commenced employment in November 2012 and worked pursuant to a series of fixed term contracts until he transitioned to indefinite term employment in December 2014.</P>
<P>29. The Defendants state that the Plaintiff was not provided with, nor signed an employment agreement which explicitly stated a fixed term duration of employment with the Corporate Defendants when he transferred to the City of Toronto. Further, the terms and conditions of his employment were not altered by the transfer and he remained an indefinite term employee.</P>
<P>30. The Corporate Defendants did not make any representations to the Plaintiff as to the expected duration of the position in Toronto. Specifically, the Corporate Defendants deny that any representations were made regarding the Plaintiff being guaranteed a minimum of three years of employment in Ontario and puts the Plaintiff to the strict proof thereof.</P>
<P>31. The Defendants specifically deny that the letter to the Canada Border Services Agency constitutes a fixed term employment agreement and puts the Plaintiff to the strict proof thereof.</P>
<P>32. The Plaintiff was terminated on February 6, 2018 due to companywide restructuring and provided eight (8) weeks of working notice and the offer for an economy flight from Toronto to the United States.</P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><N><EM>b</EM>.</N><TI><EM>The Plaintiff is not entitled to Common Law Reasonable Notice</EM></TI>
<P>33. The Defendants specifically deny that the Plaintiff is entitled to six months of common law reasonable notice as sought and puts the Plaintiff to the strict proof thereof.</P>
<P>34. The Defendants state that given the Plaintiff's age and mid-level management position, a six month notice period is excessive.</P>
<P>35. Further, the Defendants state that the Plaintiff has failed to take any steps or any reasonable and sufficient steps to mitigate his damages, if any. The Defendants further states that the Plaintiff has failed to provide any evidence that he has attempted to mitigate his damages.</P>
<P>36. The Defendants state that the Plaintiff has an affirmative obligation to mitigate any losses and damages he has sustained. To the extent that it may be found that the Plaintiff has failed to mitigate, the Defendants request that any award in the Plaintiff's favour be reduced accordingly.</P>
<P>37. Further, or in the alternative, the Defendants state that if the Plaintiff suffered the losses or damages as alleged, or at all, which is not admitted but strictly denied, then any benefits received and/or monies earned including, employment income and/or employment insurance benefits during the alleged notice period, must be deducted from any amount awarded to the Plaintiff.</P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><N><EM>c</EM>.</N><TI><UNDER>No Misrepresentation or Breach of Contract</UNDER></TI>
<P>38. The Defendants specifically deny that the Plaintiff is entitled to damages for unpaid wages.</P>
<P>39. Further, the Defendants specifically deny that the Plaintiff was advised that he would only be required to work 40 hours per week in Toronto or that the Plaintiff had such expectations.</P>
<P>40. The Defendants state that it was common in the digital media industry for managers/supervisors to work in excess of 40 hours per week during peak periods which was reflected in their significant annual salary.</P>
<P>41. The Defendants state that the Plaintiff's management level salary in the sum of $135,000 was full and fair compensation for all hours worked.</P>
<P>42. The Defendants specifically deny that the Plaintiff worked 10 to 14 hours per day or 70 to 90 hours per week and puts the Plaintiff to the strict proof thereof.</P>
<P>43. Further, the Defendants deny that the Plaintiff complained about his hours of work or his compensation at any time during his employment with the Corporate Defendants and as such, the Plaintiff is now estopped from asserting entitlement to additional compensation.</P>
<P>44. Further, the Defendants deny that the Plaintiff is entitled to damages for the alleged unpaid wages on the basis of restitution or quantum meruit and puts the Plaintiff to the strict proof thereof.</P>
<P>45. Without limiting the generality of the foregoing, the Defendants state that the Plaintiff was fully and fairly paid for all work performed and as such, there has not been an enrichment with a corresponding deprivation.</P>
<P>46. The Defendants deny that the Plaintiff is entitled to damages on the basis of negligent misrepresentation as the Defendants specifically deny that they represented to the Plaintiff that he would be guaranteed employment in Canada for three years.</P></BLOCK3></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI>DENIAL OF DAMAGES AGAINST DIRECTORS</TI>
<P>47. The Directors deny that the Plaintiff is entitled to damages for unpaid debts not exceeding six months' wages for alleged unpaid wages as the Plaintiff is not entitled to the same from the Corporate Defendants.</P>
<P>48. Further, or in the alternative, the Directors specifically deny that the alleged unpaid compensation constitutes a debt or wages pursuant to section 130 of the Ontario <EM>Business Corporations Act</EM> or section 81 of the <EM>Employment Standards Act, 2000</EM> and puts the Plaintiff to the strict proof thereof.</P>
<P>49. Further, or in the alternative, the Directors state that the Plaintiff's claim is premature as no wages have been found owing by the Corporate Defendants for which they have not paid.</P>
<P>50. The Defendants respectfully request that the Plaintiff's action be dismissed with costs on a substantial indemnity basis.</P>
